# Preparation Blueprint for SkillMap Zeroth Review Pitch  ## 1. What Your Department Expects by Zeroth Review  The guidelines clearly say zeroth review is not just for title approval but for showing that you have already done a proper literature survey and identified the research gap. Students are expected to be clear about IEEE standards, component choices, and limitations of their proposed work even at this early stage. You must also align with the outcome expectations that the project should ultimately aim at patent, Scopus/WoS-indexed publication, or a commercial product by Phase II.[1]  Zeroth review also requires prior planning with the supervisor, use of the official presentation template, and submission of approval/undertaking forms, so your pitch should already look structured and serious, not like a raw idea. Review panels will not entertain later changes in title or supervisor unless there is a strong justification, so the backup idea you pitch should be mature enough to commit to if needed.[1]  ## 2. Core Idea of SkillMap (From Your Proposal)  SkillMap is proposed as an intelligent web application that generates personalized learning paths using a combination of reinforcement learning (RL) and knowledge graphs. The platform models a subject as a graph of topics with prerequisite dependencies and recommends the next best topic and resources based on a student's evolving mastery state. A diagnostic assessment initializes the learner's profile, and an adaptive quiz engine updates their knowledge state in real time.[2]  The system includes a visual knowledge graph, RL-based topic sequencing, curated resources, mastery visualization, and a teacher dashboard for class-level insights. Technically, it plans to start with tabular Q-learning and potentially extend to DQN while encoding curriculum constraints in a directed graph structure.[2]  ## 3. Literature You Should Be Ready to Show  You will strengthen your pitch if you show that RL + knowledge graph–based learning path recommendation is an active research area and not just a random idea. Recent work has proposed RL-based frameworks integrated with knowledge graphs to generate adaptive, data-driven learning paths, modeling curriculum sequencing as a Markov Decision Process with Q-learning agents constrained by prerequisite graphs. Other studies combine knowledge graphs and deep RL to recommend personalized learning paths in domains such as English learning, updating learner mastery in real time and pruning candidate topics using Q-learning before final policy optimization.[3][4][5]  Broader AI-in-education surveys highlight that reinforcement learning, knowledge tracing, and intelligent tutoring systems are central to modern personalized learning research. Work on integrating Dynamic Knowledge Tracing with RL shows measurable improvements in prediction accuracy, completion time, and dropout reduction compared to traditional models, which you can cite as motivation for using RL instead of static recommendation rules.[6][7][8][9]  ## 4. Minimum Literature Review Packet for Zeroth Review  For zeroth review, prepare a compact but credible "mini literature packet" you can show on slides and in a 1–2 page summary:  - 2–3 core papers on RL-based curriculum/learning-path generation using knowledge graphs, e.g., RL over knowledge graphs for curriculum or English path recommendation where Q-learning selects next concepts subject to prerequisites.[4][5][3] - 1 survey or review paper on AI in education and personalized learning (covers knowledge tracing, RL, intelligent tutoring systems) to show you understand the broader landscape.[8][6] - 1–2 papers or articles on knowledge graph–based curriculum design and learning path recommendation for context on graph modeling techniques.[10][11]  On your slide, you can organize this as a table with columns: "Paper", "Technique (RL / KT / KG)", "Domain", and "Key takeaway you will reuse" so panel members see clear derivation of your idea rather than generic citations.[8][10]  ## 5. Defining Problem, Gap, and Novelty Clearly  From the guidelines, novelty and current-technology alignment are key expectations; repeated or overused topics are discouraged. You should frame your problem as: current e-learning and LMS platforms mostly provide fixed content ordering or simple prerequisite unlocking instead of adaptive, RL-driven sequencing over a knowledge graph. Existing personalized learning platforms use either static rules, traditional recommendation models, or knowledge tracing without full integration of RL for long-term learning outcome optimization.[12][1][8]  Your novelty angle for SkillMap can be stated as combining: (a) explicit knowledge graph modeling of a subject curriculum, (b) an RL agent that optimizes long-term mastery (not just immediate quiz accuracy), and (c) a tight integration of diagnostic assessment, adaptive quizzes, and teacher analytics in one system. You can also emphasize the practical contribution: a deployable web platform for common CS subjects (DSA, ML, DBMS, Python) for your department, not just a simulation.[2][8]  ## 6. Technical Scope You Should Lock Before Pitch  Before meeting your supervisor, decide on realistic technical scope that fits your time and resource constraints:  - **Representation**: Knowledge graph as a directed graph of topics and prerequisites, stored either as adjacency lists in a DB or using a graph database if time permits.[10][2] - **State**: Student state vector capturing per-topic mastery scores learned from diagnostic and ongoing quizzes, possibly using simple knowledge tracing initially and upgrading later.[7][9] - **Action space**: Selection of next topic (and optionally resource type) among currently feasible nodes that respect prerequisites.[13][3] - **RL algorithm**: Start with tabular Q-learning or simpler graph-RL algorithm demonstrated in learning path recommendation papers; keep DQN or hybrid methods as stretch goals.[14][3] - **Reward design**: Base rewards on post-topic quiz performance, time spent, and perhaps consistency (e.g., extra reward for consecutive correct answers on higher-difficulty questions).[4][8]  Having these choices written down and justified with 1–2 literature references each shows technical maturity and reassures the supervisor that the idea is implementable within a B.Tech timeline.[3][7]  ## 7. What Proof-of-Feasibility to Show at Zeroth Review  Even though this is an early review, showing some concrete artifacts greatly increases acceptance probability:  - A draft knowledge graph for at least one subject (e.g., DSA or ML) with nodes, prerequisites, and example path.[10][2] - A simple wireframe of the student dashboard: knowledge graph visualization, topic details card, quiz button, and progress indicators. - A basic architecture diagram showing modules: frontend, backend API, database, knowledge graph store, RL engine, and analytics layer.[8]  Additionally, you can show a toy RL environment prototype (e.g., in a notebook) where a Q-learning agent chooses among 5–10 topics on a small graph, just to demonstrate that the RL formulation is already clear to you. This does not have to be fully integrated with the web app at zeroth review; the goal is to convince them that the RL formulation is not hand-wavy.[14][3]  ## 8. Evaluation Plan You Can Commit To  Because final acceptance depends on either publication, patent, or productification, outline an evaluation plan early:  - **Offline simulation**: Use synthetic or simple quiz data to compare RL-based sequence vs baseline sequence (e.g., fixed syllabus order) on metrics such as cumulative reward, mastery gain, or time to mastery, similar to metrics like Normalized Learning Gain and cumulative return reported in prior work.[3][4] - **Small-scale deployment**: Plan an internal pilot with a small batch of students in one subject where you measure engagement, quiz scores, and completion rates before and after using SkillMap, inspired by AI-personalization studies that show improvements in completion and retention.[12][8]  Stating concrete metrics and comparison baselines shows you understand how to scientifically validate your system rather than only "building an app".[7][3]  ## 9. Slide Deck Structure for the Pitch  Based on your college guidelines and standard academic expectations, a crisp 8–10 slide deck could follow this flow:  1. Title, team, supervisor, thrust area, and domain (Personalized Learning, RL, Knowledge Graphs).[2] 2. Motivation: issues with one-size-fits-all curriculum, difficulty tracking individual student gaps. 3. Problem statement and clear objectives (diagnostic module, KG engine, RL agent, adaptive quizzes, teacher dashboard). 4. Literature review highlights: 3–4 bullets with key techniques and gaps from prior works.[6][4][3] 5. Proposed system architecture and module-level description. 6. Knowledge graph modeling (example subject graph) and student state representation.[10][2] 7. RL formulation: state, action, reward, algorithm choice, with an example of how a topic gets selected.[9][3] 8. Evaluation plan and expected outcomes (metrics, potential for paper/product/patent).[3][8] 9. Project timeline (Phase-wise tasks: literature, design, prototype, integration, evaluation).  This structure directly matches what review panels expect: clarity of problem, novelty, feasibility, and outcome alignment.[1]  ## 10. Concrete Next Steps for You This Week  To move from idea to a convincing backup project pitch, you can focus on a short, actionable checklist:  - Extract 4–5 key references from recent RL + KG + personalized learning papers, read at least the abstract, method, and results, and write 2–3 lines per paper in your own words.[6][4][3] - Finalize one subject for your first knowledge graph and list its topics and prerequisites in a simple spreadsheet before graph modeling.[10] - Design a simple but clean architecture diagram and UI wireframes (Figma or even PowerPoint) aligned with your proposal features.[2] - Implement a tiny Q-learning prototype over a hard-coded graph in Python to solidify your RL formulation before you talk to your supervisor.[14][3] - Draft your zeroth review slides following the outline in the previous section, ensuring they match your department’s presentation template.[1]  If you enter the meeting with these artifacts ready, you will not only satisfy the zeroth review expectations but also signal that this "backup" idea is strong enough to become a serious primary project if required.[1]











